{
  "exemplar_id": "ex_patient_question_handling_001",
  "frozen": true,
  "context_summary": "Teenage boy at a follow-up for recently re-diagnosed asthma (confirmed on pulmonary function testing a few months ago). He describes exertional breathlessness in gym class, symptoms triggered by cold air and by exposure to cats, and confusion about his two inhalers — he has been using the one that 'starts with an s' once or twice a day, didn't pick up the second, and isn't sure how they differ. Mid-interview, he interrupts with his own concern: he wants to join the Marines and has heard he can't with asthma, and asks whether his diagnosis will stop him.",
  "good_next_question": "Yeah, so it's something that we will look into today. I'm not too sure what the details are regarding that, but thank you for bringing that up and we'll be sure to look into that together. And that reminded me of a question I wanted to ask earlier — have you had pulmonary function tests done before?",
  "rationale": "This models how to handle a patient-initiated question without either derailing the diagnostic interview or dismissing the concern. The patient has surfaced something that matters enormously to him (Marines eligibility) but is not answerable in the moment and is not the immediate clinical priority. The skilled move is a three-part one: acknowledge the question as legitimate, set an honest expectation (we'll look into it, I don't have the detail right now), and bridge back to data-gathering rather than leaving the thread dangling. Crucially the doctor does not fabricate an answer about military eligibility, does not let the interview be hijacked into a long tangent, and does not brush the patient off — all three of which would damage either accuracy or rapport. The lesson this exemplar encodes is that patient questions are handled by validate-defer-redirect when they fall outside the current diagnostic objective, preserving both trust and interview control. The follow-up question chosen for the redirect (prior PFTs) is itself useful, so the bridge does real diagnostic work rather than being a stall.",
  "tags": [
    "pediatric",
    "respiratory",
    "patient_communication",
    "interview_control",
    "asthma"
  ],
